annotation: On October 20, 1997, Williams enters the rankings for the first time at 453.
Williams wins her first grand slam at the US Open after entering the top 10 that same year.
Williams climbs to no. 1 spot for first time on July 8, 2002 during a period of dominance dubbed the "Serena Slam," when she held all four grand slams simultaneously.
Due to injuries, Williams drops her no. 1 ranking to Kim Clijsters.
Suffering from depression, Williams leaves tennis for six months and received therapy. She slipped to 140 in the world.
Williams shoots to the top of the rankings for the first time since 2003 and regains the year end no. 1 spot in 2009.
Williams misses the first half of 2011 due to a pulmonary embolism and fails to defend her Wimbledon title, dropping to 175.
This is the beginning of her longest consecutive weeks at no. 1. By the end, she ties Steffi Graf's record of 186 consecutive weeks at no. 1.
Angelique Kerber takes the no. 1 spot after beating Williams in the Australian Open final that year and later in US Open final.
Williams wins the Australian Open for the 7th time, her 23rd slam total, the most of any woman in the open era, while pregnant, beating Steffi Graf's previous record of 22.
